<h2>Manual Run Through</h2>
<p>The Bellman-Ford algorithm is actually quite straight forward, because i=
t checks all edges, using the adjacency matrix. Each check is to see if a s=
horter distance can be made by going from the vertex on one side of the edg=
e, via the edge, to the vertex on the other side of the edge.</p>
<p>And this check of all edges is done <span class=3D"MathJax_Preview" styl=
e=3D"color: inherit;"></span><span id=3D"MathJax-Element-3-Frame" class=3D"=
mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML" tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"font-size: 113%; position:=
 relative;" data-mathml=3D"&lt;math xmlns=3D&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Ma=
th/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;V&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;#x2212;&lt;/mo&gt;&=
lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/math&gt;" role=3D"presentation"><span id=3D"MJXc-=
Node-9" class=3D"mjx-math" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span id=3D"MJXc-Node-10" c=
lass=3D"mjx-mrow"><span id=3D"MJXc-Node-11" class=3D"mjx-mi"><span class=3D=
"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style=3D"padding-top: 0.445em; padding-bottom: 0=
.279em; padding-right: 0.186em;">V</span></span><span id=3D"MJXc-Node-12" c=
lass=3D"mjx-mo MJXc-space2"><span class=3D"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style=
=3D"padding-top: 0.279em; padding-bottom: 0.445em;">=E2=88=92</span></span>=
<span id=3D"MJXc-Node-13" class=3D"mjx-mn MJXc-space2"><span class=3D"mjx-c=
har MJXc-TeX-main-R" style=3D"padding-top: 0.39em; padding-bottom: 0.335em;=
">1</span></span></span></span><span class=3D"MJX_Assistive_MathML" role=3D=
"presentation"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>V</mi=
><mo>=E2=88=92</mo><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> times, with <span class=
=3D"MathJax_Preview" style=3D"color: inherit;"></span><span id=3D"MathJax-E=
lement-4-Frame" class=3D"mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML" tabindex=3D"0" style=3D"f=
ont-size: 113%; position: relative;" data-mathml=3D"&lt;math xmlns=3D&quot;=
