<h2>Negative Edges in The Bellman-Ford Algorithm</h2>
<p>To say that the Bellman-Ford algorithm finds the "shortest paths" is not=
 intuitive, because how can we draw or imagine distances that are negative?=
 So, to make it easier to understand we could instead say that it is the "<=
i>cheapest</i> paths" that are found with Bellman-Ford.</p>
<p>In practice, the Bellman-Ford algorithm could for example help us to fin=
d delivering routes where the edge weights represent the cost of fuel and o=
ther things, minus the money to be made by driving that edge between those =
two vertices.</p>
